===Etymology 2===
From {{etyl|odt|nl}} {{term|sin|sīn|lang=odt}} (originally a reflexive form), from {{etyl|gem-pro|nl}} {{term/t|gem-pro|*sīnaz}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|nl}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*seyno-}}. Cognate with German {{term|sein|lang=de}}, Swedish {{term|sin|lang=sv}}. Ultimately a form of the Proto-Indo-European reflexive pronoun {{term/t|ine-pro|*swe}}, related to Russian {{term|себя|tr=sebja|lang=ru}}, Latin {{term|suus|lang=la}}, Ancient Greek {{term|ἑός|tr=heos|lang=grc}} etc.

